stimulus:
Welcome to the Symmetry and Memory Task



Press 'continue' to show the instructions.

Symmetry and Memory Task

In this task, you will try to memorize letters you see on the screen
while you also view black and white grid pictures.

In the next few minutes, you will have some practice to get you familiar
with how the task works.

It may be difficult sometimes, but please do not worry about making mistakes!

We will begin by practicing the letter part of the task.

For this practice part, letters will appear on the screen one at a time.

Try to remember each letter in the order presented.

After some letters have been shown, you will see a response screen. Your
goal is to report the letters you saw in order. If you do not remember
a particular letter, you will have the option to leave it blank.

Remember, it is very important to get the letters in the same
order as you see them.

When you are ready, you may begin the letter practice.

Please recall the letters you saw to the best of your ability. If you do not remember a particular letter, use the SKIP button.
(When you are ready to lock in your answer, press ENTER)

Now you will practice doing the symmetry judgment part of the experiment.

A black and white grid picture will appear on the screen and you have to judge if it is
symmetrical or asymetrical.

A picture is 'mirror' symmetrical if its left half is identical to the right half when flipped.
Here are examples of a symmetrical and an asymetrical picture:


To judge symmetry, imagine you were to fold each picture down the middle, like a book –
would the left half match the right half when folded onto each other?

When you have viewed the picture and determined whether it is symmetrical or not,
you can click the Yes or No button below to answer.

If you take longer than 15 seconds, it will continue automatically
and record the answer as an error.

It is very important that you make the symmetry judgment correctly.

It is also important that you try and judge the picture as quickly as you can.

When you are ready, click on the button below to try some practice problems.
You responded correctly on 3 of 3 symmetry judgments. Good job!

Now you will practice doing both parts of the experiment at the same time.

In the next practice set, you will be given one grid picture to judge.
Then letter will appear on the screen. Try to remember the letter.

It is very important to make the symmetry judgment as quickly and accurately as possible.

Just as before, once you have make the symmetry judgment, you can click Yes or No.
Note that you will no longer see Correct or Incorrect feedback.

After the letter goes away, another grid picture will appear, and then
another letter.

At the end of each set of letters and grids, you will recall the letters to the best
of your ability. Remember, try your best to get the letters in the correct order.

It is important to quickly and accurately make the symmetry judgments.

On the feedback screen, if you are not doing well at the symmetry judgments,
you will also see a warning in the middle. This indicates your percent
correct for the grid pictures for the entire experiment.

It is very important for you to keep accuracy at least at 85%: We can only use
data where the participant was at least 85% accurate on the judgments. Therefore,
please try your best to perform well on the symmetry judgments, at the same time
doing your best to recall as many letters as possible.

Click the button to try some practice problems.

Please recall the letters you saw to the best of your ability. If you do not remember a particular letter, use the SKIP button.
(When you are ready to lock in your answer, press ENTER)
